6. Words are divided by meaning into
a) unambiguous and polysemous;
b) proper and common;
c) similar and opposite.
7. Words are distinguished into groups based on sound or spelling
a) homonyms and paronyms;
b) homographs and homophones;
c) homonyms and homographs.
8. According to emotional coloring, words can be
a) purely emotional and dependent emotional;
b) neutral and emotional;
c) solemn and everyday.
9. According to origin, words are divided into
a) archaisms and neologisms;
b) literary and dialectal;
c) native and borrowed.
10. According to the activity of usage, words can be
a) active and passive;
b) common and scientific terms;
c) business stamps and figurative-artistic.
11. Emotionally colored vocabulary is used in the following styles:
a) journalistic;
b) scientific;
c) artistic.
